  "prompt": "Why are Hela cells immortal?",
  "response": "Hela cells are immortal due to several key genetic and molecular characteristics:\n\n1. Telomerase activation\n- Telomerase, an enzyme that rebuilds telomeres, is continuously active in HeLa cells\n- This prevents telomere shortening during cell division, allowing cells to divide indefinitely\n\n2. HPV infection\n- The cells originated from cervical cancer cells infected with human papillomavirus (HPV)\n- HPV introduces oncogenic proteins (E6 and E7) that interfere with normal cell cycle regulation\n\n3. P53 mutation\n- The tumor suppressor gene p53 is mutated in HeLa cells\n- This mutation prevents normal cell cycle checkpoints and apoptosis (programmed cell death)\n\n4. Multiple chromosomal abnormalities\n- HeLa cells have an abnormal number of chromosomes\n- These genetic mutations contribute to uncontrolled cell growth\n\n5. Origin from aggressive cancer\n- The original cells were derived from an aggressive cervical cancer tumor\n- This inherently gave them properties of rapid, uncontrolled proliferation\n\nThese combined factors allow HeLa cells to continuously divide and reproduce, making them \"immortal\" in laboratory conditions. They were the first human cell line successfully cultured and have been extensively used in medical research since the 1950s.",
